<br>
The hound materialized from the thin mountainous air, and bowed before his mistress.  Hecate looked into her hound's mind and understood.  It appears that one of the Furies had left Tartarus and was roaming the world, most likely on some personal vendetta.  Hecate pondered this piece of information.  The Furies united could be a serious problem, but a single Fury would be manageable.  The Furies sought retribution for some sort of injustice they feel has been done to them or to someone they have a personal stake in.  Hecate knew she hadn't done anything directly against them, so she most likely was in the clear.  The guys on the other hand had decided to do things a bit differently.  Therefore most likely they were the ones being hunted.  Yet the Furies never did do things logically.  Their temperament was truly explosive, and anyone caught within the blast, in their eyes would be just as equally guilty.  Guilty by association.<br>
<br>
Hecate couldn't be troubled by that right now.  She sent her hound back to its task.  Right now she had something a bit more important.  She was about to enter this cave, which housed a major temple to the Cyclopes, Titans of the One Eye.  Although the Cyclopes should have been imprisoned in Tartarus, Hecate wasn't sure if they were one of the ones that had escaped.  Therefore there was a chance that she would be meeting them within this cave.<br>
<br>
As with the encouter with the Fates, whenever entering the domain of any of the deities, whether they were currently being worshipped or not, always gave them the upper hand.  In your own domain, you ruled.  Once you stepped out, the playing field became more balanced.  Well she was about to enter the Cyclopes domain, and according to her records, there were three of them.  Although the Cyclopes weren't gods, they did however have the power to rival them.  It had truly been difficult to finally defeat imprison the Titans.  So now, if she entered and all three were inside, she most likely would be able to leave only after a serious and painful battle had been fought.<br>
<br>
